because I led her to believe...

235
00:16:57,245 --> 00:16:59,975
that as the owner of KNOW magazine,
I had some pull with my staff.

236
00:17:00,048 --> 00:17:02,881
Then pull your staff with one of
your other writers. I'm not doing it.

237
00:17:02,951 --> 00:17:04,885
No, it can't be anyone else.

238
00:17:04,953 --> 00:17:09,253
The best thing I have to offer
a woman is the same as the best
thing you have to offer... you.

239
00:17:09,324 --> 00:17:12,384
But I'm all tied up, Mac.
I'm using me.

240
00:17:12,461 --> 00:17:14,952
Oh, come on! It'll be fun.

241
00:17:15,030 --> 00:17:17,294
- You like fun.
- Fun?

242
00:17:17,365 --> 00:17:21,096
Interviewing a man-hating embittered
New England spinster librarian?

243
00:17:21,169 --> 00:17:22,761
How do you know what she's like?

244
00:17:22,838 --> 00:17:25,466
Who else would write a book
called Down With Love?

245
00:17:25,540 --> 00:17:29,601
You don't have to be a Nazi
rocket scientist to figure that out.

246
00:17:29,678 --> 00:17:33,478
Catch, please, please, please, please?

247
00:17:33,582 --> 00:17:36,710
I hope you won't be disappointed.

248
00:17:41,256 --> 00:17:43,190
[Gasps]

249
00:18:04,913 --> 00:18:09,213
Oh, Vikki, it's adorable.

250
00:18:09,284 --> 00:18:12,151
[Phone Ringing]

251
00:18:12,220 --> 00:18:15,519
My first New York phone call!

252
00:18:15,590 --> 00:18:19,492
It must be KNOW magazine.
No one else has your number.

253
00:18:20,695 --> 00:18:22,754
It must be Catcher Block!

254
00:18:22,831 --> 00:18:24,822
- Oh!
- Oh!

255
00:18:26,835 --> 00:18:29,827
- This is Barbara Novak.
- This is Catcher Block.

256
00:18:29,905 --> 00:18:33,568
Catcher Block.
Catcher Block.

257
00:18:33,642 --> 00:18:36,611
- KNOW magazine.
- Oh, yes, of course.

258
00:18:36,678 --> 00:18:39,511
What can I do for you,
Mr. Block?

259
00:18:39,581 --> 00:18:42,072
I think it's what I can do for you,
Miss Novak.

260
00:18:42,150 --> 00:18:44,880
I'd like to invite you to lunch
so we can discuss your book.

261
00:18:44,953 --> 00:18:46,944
That sounds very nice...

262
00:18:47,022 --> 00:18:50,082
but I'll have to check my schedule
to see when I'm available.

263
00:18:50,158 --> 00:18:53,559
We've already ordered. Can you be in
the Mahogany Room in ten minutes?

264
00:18:53,628 --> 00:18:56,222
I'm afraid that will be
impossible, Mr. Block.

265
00:18:56,298 --> 00:18:58,858
- Some other time, then.
- Right.

266
00:18:58,934 --> 00:19:01,732
I'll see you in 15.

267
00:19:01,803 --> 00:19:03,805
[Both Squealing]

268
00:19:03,938 --> 00:19:08,432
Catch, you are the best friend a guy
with 20 diagnosed neuroses ever had.

269
00:19:08,509 --> 00:19:11,501
We've been friends a long time.
I knew you when you only had 12.

270
00:19:11,579 --> 00:19:13,740
This is great!
I'll be right back.

271
00:19:13,815 --> 00:19:16,648
Gotta go put in my shoe lifts.

272
00:19:20,421 --> 00:19:23,254
- Guess who.
- As if I'd need to guess.

273
00:19:23,324 --> 00:19:25,815
- Hmm. Tell me my name.
- Tell me you love me.

274
00:19:25,893 --> 00:19:27,884
Blimey, Catch.
You know I love you.

275
00:19:27,962 --> 00:19:31,693
And I love you too... Gwendolyn.

276
00:19:31,766 --> 00:19:33,757
Oh.

277
00:19:35,937 --> 00:19:38,428
- How long's your layover?
- Never long enough.

278
00:19:38,506 --> 00:19:41,100
There's always time for a matinee.

279
00:20:34,729 --> 00:20:39,189
Well, hello, Peter.
Barbara Novak, Peter MacMannus.

280
00:20:39,267 --> 00:20:41,758
Nice to meet you,
Mr. MacMannus.

281
00:20:41,836 --> 00:20:45,294
- [Vikki] Where's Mr. Block?
- Yes, where's Mr. Block?

282
00:20:45,373 --> 00:20:48,865
I, uh, I don't know. Henri.

283
00:20:48,943 --> 00:20:51,673
- Where is Mr. Block?
- I don't know.

284
00:20:51,746 --> 00:20:54,647
A Mr. Block for you,
Mr. MacMannus?

285
00:20:54,715 --> 00:20:56,683
Ah.

286
00:20:56,751 --> 00:20:58,685
Here he is now.

287
00:21:02,123 --> 00:21:04,114
- Catcher!
- Mac.

288
00:21:04,191 --> 00:21:07,991
- Where are ya?
- Something sprang up. Is she there?

289
00:21:08,062 --> 00:21:11,463
- Yes, she is.
- Let me speak to the spinster.

290
00:21:11,532 --> 00:21:14,695
Mr. Block would like
to speak with you.

291
00:21:18,673 --> 00:21:21,540
- This is Barbara Novak.
- I'm so sorry, Miss Novak.

292
00:21:21,609 --> 00:21:23,543
The darndest thing.

293
00:21:23,611 --> 00:21:26,774
I was waiting for you at the bar,
and a little English foxhound...

294
00:21:26,847 --> 00:21:30,146
walked right in, came up to me
and started nuzzling me.

295
00:21:30,217 --> 00:21:33,209
She seemed so lost, and she didn't
want to go with anyone else...

296
00:21:33,287 --> 00:21:35,448
so I just had to take care of her.

297
00:21:35,523 --> 00:21:38,287
Mr. Block, that is so thoughtful.

298
00:21:38,359 --> 00:21:41,419
I remember reading that the true test
of a man's character...

299
00:21:41,495 --> 00:21:43,986
is how he treats
a defenseless creature.

300
00:21:44,065 --> 00:21:47,694
Tell me, Mr. Block,
how is the little bitch now?

301
00:21:47,768 --> 00:21:50,464
Well, I've got her
all nestled in a box...

302
00:21:50,538 --> 00:21:54,133
but I don't think she'll be content
until I'm holding her.

303
00:21:54,208 --> 00:21:57,006
Miss Novak, could we
rain check until dinner?

304
00:21:57,078 --> 00:21:59,137
Of course.

305
00:21:59,213 --> 00:22:02,205
Well, good-bye, Mr. Block.
Until dinner.

306
00:22:02,283 --> 00:22:04,274
Good-bye.

307
00:22:05,453 --> 00:22:09,184
[Orchestra: Dramatic]

308
00:22:22,103 --> 00:22:24,094
This is Barbara Novak.

309
00:22:24,171 --> 00:22:26,833
Miss Novak, I am so sorry.

310
00:22:26,907 --> 00:22:29,740
- The darndest thing.
- Yes, Mr. Block?

311
00:22:29,810 --> 00:22:32,938
I'm out in the park
with my little French poodle...

312
00:22:33,014 --> 00:22:36,950
and she's just not ready to go in yet,
if you know what I mean.

313
00:22:37,018 --> 00:22:39,748
Oh, I do,
but here's a little advice...

314
00:22:39,820 --> 00:22:41,913
from a farm girl to a city boy.

315
00:22:41,989 --> 00:22:45,550
You'll find that if you stick
a little twig in her bottom...

316
00:22:45,626 --> 00:22:48,618
she'll remember why she went out
with you in the first place.

317
00:22:48,696 --> 00:22:50,857
I'll keep that in mind.

318
00:22:50,931 --> 00:22:52,922
Miss Novak, I hate to ask...

319
00:22:53,000 --> 00:22:55,468
but could we rain check
until breakfast?

320
00:22:55,536 --> 00:22:58,198
Of course.
Good-bye, Mr. Block.

321
00:22:58,272 --> 00:23:00,263
Until breakfast.

322
00:23:02,109 --> 00:23:05,442
- [Bat Hitting Ball]
- [Crowd Cheering]

323
00:23:06,447 --> 00:23:08,381
I... just don't know.

324
00:23:08,449 --> 00:23:10,508
It's not like Catch to be late.

325
00:23:10,584 --> 00:23:13,815
No. He usually calls
to cancel right on time.

326
00:23:13,888 --> 00:23:16,015
Oh, Barbara,
I'm sure he'll call.

327
00:23:16,090 --> 00:23:19,116
I mean, come.

328
00:23:19,193 --> 00:23:22,128
Elkie and I missed you
at lunch yesterday, Gwendolyn.

329
00:23:22,196 --> 00:23:25,097
Oh, I, uh, took in a matinee...

330
00:23:25,166 --> 00:23:27,100
with Catcher Block.

331
00:23:28,836 --> 00:23:30,770
Is that so?

332
00:23:30,838 --> 00:23:33,466
But Elkie and I missed you
at dinner last night, Yvette.

333
00:23:33,541 --> 00:23:36,374
Oh, I took in a night game...
with Catcher Block.

334
00:23:40,014 --> 00:23:43,472
- I told him I'd give up flying for him.
- I did too.!

335
00:23:43,551 --> 00:23:46,850
- Now I wonder if he ever loved me.
- I wonder if he even cared.

336
00:23:49,123 --> 00:23:51,148
[Both]
I wonder what's keeping Elkie!

337
00:24:01,602 --> 00:24:03,536
This is Barbara Novak.

338
00:24:03,604 --> 00:24:06,767
I'm so sorry, Miss Novak.
The darndest thing.

339
00:24:06,841 --> 00:24:10,971
I got waylaid by the sweetest Swedish lap
hound, who kept me up half the night...

340
00:24:11,045 --> 00:24:13,673
and I'm afraid I'm still in bed.

341
00:24:13,747 --> 00:24:16,739
My! You do get waylaid.

342
00:24:16,817 --> 00:24:19,980
- Would you care for another beverage?
- Yeah, sure. Thank you.

343
00:24:20,054 --> 00:24:24,252
- I beg your pardon?
- I was saying thank you.
You're very understanding.

344
00:24:24,325 --> 00:24:26,725
Could we rain check until lunch?

345
00:24:26,794 --> 00:24:28,955
Oh, Mr. Block.

346
00:24:29,029 --> 00:24:31,190
You can take your rain check...

347
00:24:31,265 --> 00:24:34,098
and as we say on the farm
at harvest time...

348
00:24:34,168 --> 00:24:37,103
put it where the sun
does not shine!

349
00:24:37,171 --> 00:24:40,663
Miss Novak, if you're looking
to get dinner, then just say so.

350
00:24:40,741 --> 00:24:44,541
[Scoffing Laugh]
Mr. Block...

351
00:24:44,612 --> 00:24:46,773
I wouldn't meet with you...

352
00:24:46,847 --> 00:24:50,010
in a hundred years!

353
00:24:50,084 --> 00:24:52,279
- Good-bye, Mr. Block...
- [Punching Sound]

354
00:24:52,353 --> 00:24:54,844
Forever!

355
00:24:54,922 --> 00:24:57,618
[Thunder Rumbling]

356
00:25:00,261 --> 00:25:02,889
Mr. MacMannus,
thank you for your trouble.

357
00:25:02,963 --> 00:25:05,227
Not at all.

358
00:25:05,299 --> 00:25:08,393
Vikki, I'll call a taxi.

359
00:25:12,373 --> 00:25:15,342
- Guess this means we're through.
- Oh, it's sad, isn't it?

360
00:25:15,409 --> 00:25:18,401
This is the first time I've had to
eliminate having a future with a man...

361
00:25:18,479 --> 00:25:21,380
before we've even had a chance
to have had a past.

362
00:25:21,448 --> 00:25:23,541
Good-bye, Mr. MacMannus.

363
00:25:30,724 --> 00:25:34,285
- [Band]
- [Peter] It was nice while it lasted.

364
00:25:34,361 --> 00:25:38,559
I haven't had dinner and breakfast
with the same woman since I had a nanny.

365
00:25:38,632 --> 00:25:41,624
I'm sorry, Peter, but Vikki
is not the only girl for you.

366
00:25:41,702 --> 00:25:43,693
That's why I brought you here.

367
00:25:43,771 --> 00:25:46,672
You brought me here...
because we're buddies, right?

368
00:25:46,740 --> 00:25:48,674
Bosom buddies.

369
00:25:48,742 --> 00:25:52,405
- [Men Whistling]
- [Continues]

370
00:26:02,957 --> 00:26:05,050
Get a load of those rockets.

371
00:26:05,125 --> 00:26:08,891
- Here's to antigravity.
- Stay with me, buddy.
You'll get the spins.

372
00:26:08,963 --> 00:26:11,796
And whatever you do,
don't close your eyes.

373
00:26:11,865 --> 00:26:14,629
Don't close your eyes.

374
00:26:14,902 --> 00:26:18,360
Open your eyes. Open your eyes.

375
00:26:20,608 --> 00:26:23,008
Ta-da! It's your book.

376
00:26:23,077 --> 00:26:26,376
On sale, Scribners, Fifth Avenue.

377
00:26:26,447 --> 00:26:28,438
One?

378
00:26:29,617 --> 00:26:31,608
Just one?

379
00:26:32,753 --> 00:26:36,314
All that work,
and-and-and-and one?

380
00:26:36,390 --> 00:26:40,486
If somebody buys it,
well, then there will be none.

381
00:26:40,561 --> 00:26:43,655
It will be as if
it never even existed.

382
00:26:43,731 --> 00:26:47,223
No, no.
Doubleday also has one.

383
00:26:47,301 --> 00:26:49,735
- [Bell Dings]
- Mmm.

384
00:26:49,803 --> 00:26:53,136
I know you're thinking this is
a real setback, but I promise you...

385
00:26:53,207 --> 00:26:55,198
I will think of something.

386
00:26:57,444 --> 00:26:59,812
If only we could get your book
on The Ed Sullivan Show.

387
00:26:59,812 --> 00:27:01,712
If only we could get your book
on The Ed Sullivan Show.

388
00:27:01,780 --> 00:27:04,044
Yeah.

389
00:27:04,116 --> 00:27:07,950
How exactly do you get a book
on The Ed Sullivan Show?

390
00:27:09,354 --> 00:27:11,982
[Barbara]
Vikki, you're incredible.

391
00:27:12,057 --> 00:27:15,117
She wasn't even on the bill.
How did they fit her into the lineup?

392
00:27:15,194 --> 00:27:17,128
- [Audience Applauding]
- Oh, the best luck.

393
00:27:17,196 --> 00:27:20,427
The Singing Nun fell off her scooter
coming across the Triborough Bridge.

394
00:27:20,499 --> 00:27:22,399
I guess somebody up there likes me.

395
00:27:22,467 --> 00:27:25,800
[Ed Sullivan]
We have for you a really big surprise...

396
00:27:25,871 --> 00:27:29,363
because to coincide
with the arrival of the new book...

397
00:27:29,441 --> 00:27:31,841
Down With Love...

398
00:27:31,910 --> 00:27:35,573
which this week is at your booksellers
from coast to coast...

399
00:27:35,647 --> 00:27:39,481
we have a very, very special
friend of our show...

400
00:27:39,551 --> 00:27:41,951
to do a song of that book.

401
00:27:42,020 --> 00:27:45,148
Now, I want a really big,
warm welcome...

402
00:27:45,224 --> 00:27:47,385
forJudy Garland...

403
00:27:47,459 --> 00:27:49,393
right on this stage.

404
00:27:49,461 --> 00:27:53,261
[Band]

405
00:28:35,207 --> 00:28:37,801
Yes, ma'am. Down With Love
by Barbara Novak.

406
00:28:37,876 --> 00:28:40,470
It's called Down With Love
by Barbara Novak.

407
00:29:00,165 --> 00:29:02,929
- [Laughing]
- Yes!

408
00:29:19,384 --> 00:29:22,114
[Bicycle Bells Dinging]

409
00:29:50,148 --> 00:29:52,810
[All Screaming]

410
00:30:09,167 --> 00:30:12,694
[Screaming]

411
00:30:12,771 --> 00:30:14,705
[Gigging, Squealing]

412
00:30:15,774 --> 00:30:18,675
[Applause]

413
00:30:39,531 --> 00:30:41,522
You said she was a spinster.

414
00:30:41,600 --> 00:30:44,262
I've never used
the word "spinster" in my life.

415
00:30:44,336 --> 00:30:47,965
Okay, once, when I told my mother
it was technically incorrect
to call her son a spinster.

416
00:30:48,040 --> 00:30:50,508
- You said she was a brunette.
- I did not!

417
00:30:50,575 --> 00:30:53,100
She sure didn't sound like a blond
on the telephone.

418
00:30:53,178 --> 00:30:56,670
- You still want to date Vikki?
- Of course. You think I
want to die a spinster?

419
00:30:56,748 --> 00:31:00,650
- Tell her I'll do the cover story.
- You are the best friend...

420
00:31:00,719 --> 00:31:03,813
Just... call.

421
00:31:03,889 --> 00:31:08,349
[Man] Not sinceJohannes Gutenberg's
invention of the printing press...

422
00:31:08,427 --> 00:31:12,420
which changed forever
the landscape of man's destiny...

423
00:31:12,497 --> 00:31:16,399
has one book reached so many
and achieved so much...

424
00:31:16,468 --> 00:31:18,868
reminding all of us here today...

425
00:31:18,937 --> 00:31:23,067
of the noble goal which called us
to toil in the field of publishing...

426
00:31:23,141 --> 00:31:25,405
to begin with...

427
00:31:25,477 --> 00:31:27,411
sales.

428
00:31:27,479 --> 00:31:31,609
So here's to Banner House's
new number-one author...

429
00:31:31,683 --> 00:31:35,346
and our new number-one editor.

430
00:31:35,420 --> 00:31:37,354
Say cheers, everyone.

431
00:31:38,490 --> 00:31:40,424
[All]
Cheers.

432
00:31:40,492 --> 00:31:42,983
Those men are livid, B.N.

433
00:31:43,061 --> 00:31:45,552
You're a hit.
You're bigger than the pill.

434
00:31:45,630 --> 00:31:48,258
Oh, talk about big, V.H.

435
00:31:48,333 --> 00:31:51,496
This office is huge. Congratulations.

436
00:31:51,570 --> 00:31:53,504
We did it.

437
00:31:53,572 --> 00:31:58,032
Well, hello, Gladys!
You look wonderful.

438
00:31:58,110 --> 00:32:01,739
As you told me, Barbara,
it's never too late. [Giggles]

439
00:32:01,813 --> 00:32:03,940
Oh, Vikki, Peter MacMannus
called again.

440
00:32:04,015 --> 00:32:06,006
Now it's every half hour.

441
00:32:07,652 --> 00:32:09,711
[Both]
Tell him we're too busy.

442
00:32:09,788 --> 00:32:14,054
- What do you mean? "Too busy"?
- You know what it means.

443
00:32:14,126 --> 00:32:16,356
[Peter]
They hate us.

444
00:32:16,428 --> 00:32:18,419
Too busy?

445
00:32:18,497 --> 00:32:21,933
Kennedy, Khrushchev and Castro weren't
too busy during the Cuban Missile Crisis...

446
00:32:22,000 --> 00:32:23,934
to sit down and talk to me...

447
00:32:24,002 --> 00:32:27,028
but this Down With Love chick
is too busy.

448
00:32:27,105 --> 00:32:29,801
Doing what? Eating chocolate?

449
00:32:29,875 --> 00:32:32,639
[Man On TV]
I'm sorry, panel. You've been stumped.

450
00:32:32,711 --> 00:32:36,169
- The author of the best seller,
Down With Love...
- It's Novak!

451
00:32:36,248 --> 00:32:38,773
- Barbara Novak.
- [Audience Applauding]

452
00:32:38,850 --> 00:32:41,410
Barbara, I know every woman
bought your book...

453
00:32:41,486 --> 00:32:45,718
and every man sneaked out and bought it
to find out what their women were reading.

454
00:32:45,790 --> 00:32:47,917
- That's when the sales doubled.
- [Laughing]

455
00:32:47,993 --> 00:32:50,427
[Man] But then they tripled.
How did that happen?

456
00:32:50,495 --> 00:32:54,397
It seems that church groups
in the Bible belt were so zealous...

457
00:32:54,466 --> 00:32:57,560
about being seen burning my book...

458
00:32:57,636 --> 00:33:00,628
that every time they had a bonfire,
they would call and reorder...

459
00:33:00,705 --> 00:33:03,538
so that they could have another one.

460
00:33:06,545 --> 00:33:09,275
Now, I've heard a lot of talk
about chapter eight...

461
00:33:09,347 --> 00:33:12,316
about the worst kind of man,
the kind every woman should avoid.

462
00:33:12,384 --> 00:33:13,874
What's that title again?

463
00:33:13,952 --> 00:33:18,412
"Men who change women as often
as they change their shirts."

464
00:33:18,490 --> 00:33:21,926
[Man] And have you met a lot
of that kind of man in your research?

465
00:33:21,993 --> 00:33:25,554
[Chuckles] You're not asking me
to name names, are you?

466
00:33:25,630 --> 00:33:28,463
- No, of course not.
- [Barbara Laughing]

467
00:33:28,533 --> 00:33:31,093
Catcher Block.

468
00:33:31,169 --> 00:33:33,729
[Audience]
Ohh.!

469
00:33:38,743 --> 00:33:41,803
Wow!

470
00:33:41,880 --> 00:33:44,246
Four million women
in the naked city...

471
00:33:44,316 --> 00:33:48,912
